<h2>Notification</h2>

<div class="uk-padding uk-box-shadow-medium uk-margin">
  <UkButton @label="Default" @onClick={{this.default}} />
  <UkButton @label="Primary" @onClick={{this.primary}} />
  <UkButton @label="Success" @onClick={{this.success}} />
  <UkButton @label="Warning" @onClick={{this.warning}} />
  <UkButton @label="Danger" @onClick={{this.danger}} />
</div>

<UkSwitcher @animation="uk-animation-fade" as |switcher|>
  <switcher.nav @type="tab" as |nav|>
    <nav.component as |tab|>
      <tab.item>Usage</tab.item>
    </nav.component>
  </switcher.nav>

  <switcher.content as |content|>
    <content.item>
      To use the
      <code>notification</code>
      service simply inject it into your
      <code>Route</code>,
      <code>Controller</code>
      or
      <code>Component</code>. Then you can use the
      <code>default</code>,
      <code>primary</code>,
      <code>success</code>,
      <code>warning</code>
      and
      <code>danger</code>
      methods to display a message.
      <CodeSnippet @name="notification.js" />
      All of the methods take the same arguments:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <code>message (String)</code>
          The content of the notification
        </li>
        <li>
          <code>options (Object)</code>
          Additional options. Available options are listed
          <a
            href="https://getuikit.com/docs/notification#component-options"
          >here</a>. This argument is optional. You can also
          <LinkTo @route="index">configure your notifications globally</LinkTo>.
        </li>
      </ul>
      Each method returns a
      <code>Promise</code>
      which is resolved as soon as the notification closes.
    </content.item>
  </switcher.content>
</UkSwitcher>